data.reasoningText:
The issue is with the InMemory provider and Include/ThenInclude behavior. Looking at the controller's Index action:

```csharp
viewModel.Instructors = db.Instructors
    .Include(i => i.OfficeAssignment)
    .Include(i => i.CourseAssignments)
        .ThenInclude(c => c.Course)
            .ThenInclude(d => d.Department)
    .OrderBy(i => i.LastName);

if (id != null)
{
    ViewBag.InstructorID = id.Value;
    viewModel.Courses = viewModel.Instructors.Where(
        i => i.ID == id.Value).Single().CourseAssignments.Select(s => s.Course);
}
```

The problem is that when I re-query the already-materialized `viewModel.Instructors` collection with `.Where(...).Single()`, the InMemory provider isn't properly maintaining the navigation properties that were eagerly loaded. The CourseAssignments collection appears empty even though the includes were specified. I suspect the issue is in how I'm seeding the test data—when entities are added separately rather than through their navigation properties, the InMemory provider might not be automatically fixing up the relationships unless the entities are being actively tracked.

Let me trace through the seed logic to verify the CourseAssignments are actually being persisted, and then check if the Include is working correctly in the subsequent query. The error message is pointing to line 50 which still has `Assert.NotEmpty`, but I removed that in my updated code—this must be a cached build issue. I need to do a clean rebuild to pick up the changes.
